{{hatnote|Not to be confused with the 16th-century conquistador of the same name, [[Gil González Dávila]].}}
'''Gil González de Ávila''' (1570 or 1577 – 1658) was a [[Spain|Spanish]] biographer and antique collector.{{efn|also written '''Gil González d'Ávila'''{{sfn|Baynes|1878|p=157}} and '''Gil González Dávila'''}}

==Life==
He was born and died at [[Ávila, Spain|Ávila]]. He spent his early years in [[Rome]], where he was educated at the residence of Cardinal Deza.  He returned to Spain when he was 20 and settled in [[Salamanca]].  He was called to [[Madrid]] and made historiographer to the [[Crown of Castile]] in 1612, and for the Indies in 1641. Of his numerous works, the most valuable are his ''Teatro de las Grandezas des Madrid'' (Madrid, 1623, sqq.), and his ''Teatro Eclesiastico'', descriptive of the metropolitan churches and cathedrals of [[Castile (historical region)|Castile]], with lives of the prelates (Madrid, 1645–1653, 4 vols.){{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=64}}

